57:52.720 --> 57:56.400
But sooner or later, you are going
to get bored watching Apollo 13

57:56.600 --> 57:59.040
and you might want to go
 for a walk outside.

57:59.080 --> 58:04.040
If you do, you have to exit through-
 the rather unusual back door.

58:04.120 --> 58:09.200
Here we go.
My feet are entering the suit.

58:09.320 --> 58:14.680
My gentleman's area is compressed
by the crotch of the spacesuit.

58:16.520 --> 58:19.560
I have my hands in the space suit.

58:19.600 --> 58:22.200
Leak check complete.

58:22.440 --> 58:25.440
Closing the hatch
 in the Lunar Rover.

58:30.320 --> 58:35.000
That is quite a giant leap
for a very unsteady man.

58:35.200 --> 58:38.640
I would now like to
perform a short tribute

58:38.760 --> 58:41.400
to the late Alan Shepard Junior,

58:41.680 --> 58:45.360
one of only 12 men
to have walked on the moon,

58:45.480 --> 58:48.120
and the only man to have done this.

58:51.240 --> 58:54.080
Houston,
the Eagle is going for a birdie.

58:58.760 --> 58:59.760
There we go.

59:01.480 --> 59:03.240
Miles and miles and miles.

59:07.640 --> 59:10.120
I'd like to be deadly
serious for a moment.

59:10.360 --> 59:15.440
This is the most fabulous vehicle
I have ever driven. Ever.

59:15.640 --> 59:17.440
But there is a problem with it.

59:17.560 --> 59:20.840
Not a technical problem,
it is the President.

59:20.880 --> 59:24.960
He has cancelled all the
funding for the next moon mission.

59:26.200 --> 59:28.440
Because that is what
makes the ship go up.

59:28.600 --> 59:32.080
No bucks, no Buck Rogers.

59:34.520 --> 59:38.160
That means, if you're a kid,
you will never have the thrill

59:38.360 --> 59:41.480
of getting up in the middle
of the night, like I did,

59:41.600 --> 59:45.280
to watch the funny little car
hooning about on the moon.

59:45.480 --> 59:47.720
Yahoo!

59:47.840 --> 59:50.360
That was all four wheels
off the ground there.

59:50.440 --> 59:53.600
This is really some machine.

59:53.680 --> 59:59.760
This piece of film I am watching
now shows men leaving the surface
of the moon for the last time.

01:00:00.080 --> 01:00:06.800
That is the ascent stage of the
Apollo 17 lunar module blasting off-
from the lunar surface.

01:00:06.880 --> 01:00:12.040
That bit of film was captured
with a remote camera
mounted on the moon buggy.

01:00:12.120 --> 01:00:15.280
Which means, obviously,
that the moon buggy was left behind.

01:00:18.000 --> 01:00:21.760
It does make me sort of sad, really,
to think of that amazing car

01:00:21.840 --> 01:00:26.920
being left up there,
gathering moon dust for eternity.

01:00:27.000 --> 01:00:31.160
But if you ask me, it is not
half as sad as a moon buggy

01:00:31.400 --> 01:00:34.200
that will never go up there at all.

01:00:36.480 --> 01:00:38.480
APPLAUSE

01:00:39.800 --> 01:00:42.680
I understand the
financial considerations,

01:00:42.760 --> 01:00:45.600
but it is sad, isn't it?
Yes, it makes me sad.

01:00:45.880 --> 01:00:47.040
I tell you what else is sad.

01:00:47.240 --> 01:00:51.680
That is not only the end of this
show, it is the end of this series.

01:00:51.960 --> 01:00:53.920
Thank you very much for
watching, though,

01:00:54.160 --> 01:00:56.560
we will see you again in June.
Take care. Goodnight.

